rking with writing and film from Africa, South Asia, and beyond, Wenzel takes a contrapuntal approach to sites and subjects dispersed across space and time. Reading for the planet, Wenzel shows, means reading from near to there: across experiential divides, between specific sites, at more than one scale.Impressive in its disciplinary breadth, Wenzel’s book fuses insights from political ecology, geography, anthropology, history, and law, while drawing on active debates between postcolonial theory and world literature, as well as scholarship on the Anthropocene and the material turn. In doing so, the book shows the importance of the literary to environmental thought and practice, elaborating how a supple understanding of cultural imagination and narrative logics can foster more robust accounts of global inequality and energize movements for justice and livable futures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEnvironmental degradationzDeveloping countries. 0aNature in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comparative Literature.2bisacsh  aAnthropocene.  acorporation.  aecocriticism.  aenvironmental humanities.  aenvironmental justice.  aglobalization.  aimperialism.  anew materialism.  apostcolonial.  aworld literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311072273440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823286805zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823286805423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823286805/original  a978-3-11-072273-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13EN